The paper generally aims to investigate the taxonomy of Nervilia species observed in the University of the Philippines Visayas Miagao Campus. Specifically, it seeks to:

(1) describe the morphology of Nervilia species observed in the UP Visayas Miagao Campus using descriptive terminology and measurements;
(2) identify Nervilia species in the campus following the morphological species concept through plant examinations and measurement, comparison with herbarium sheets, and published descriptions, including protologues;
(3) apply DNA barcoding methods to generate preliminary molecular data and compare these with reference sequences from online databases to support or refine species identification; and
(4) investigate the habitat preferences, phenology, and associated species of Nervilia populations observed within the UP Visayas Miagao Campus.

Our study focuses on the comparative analysis of bat gut microbiota in beach forest ecosystems. Specifically, we aim to:

1. Assess bat species composition and diversity within selected sites;
2. Characterize and compare gut microbiota composition across bat species using 16S rRNA amplicon sequencing;
3. Interpret potential indicators of bat health based on microbiome profiles; and
4. Explore correlations among feeding guild, diet, and microbiota composition in relation to food resource availability.

We have already completed DNA extraction from fecal samples and are currently at the stage of DNA quantification and quality assessment.
